,"id":"44889"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54769"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department after a four metre fall onto the left side of his chest at work. He is alert and anxious, and is complaining of left-sided sharp chest pain and shortness of breath. His blood pressure is 90/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min, respiratory rate 30/min and oxygen saturation 94% on 15L supplemental oxygen. There is a 5cm laceration with extensive bruising on the lateral aspect of his chest and paradoxical respiration on that side. A chest X-ray shows fractures of four contiguous ribs on the left side and a haemopneumothorax. The right side appears normal. A chest drain is inserted and 1800mL of blood drains immediately.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest indication that this patient needs an emergency thoracotomy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The volume of blood drained","The poor oxygen saturation","The low blood pressure","The flail chest","The chest wall laceration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has suffered a major thoracic injury, as judged by the nature of the accident and the clinical picture of hypovolaemic shock. He is hypotensive and the large \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of blood\u003C/strong\u003E exiting from the chest drain indicates active haemorrhage. Whilst this might be no more than bleeding from intercostal vessels, the patient will require prompt surgical intervention to identify and control the source of the bleeding, which at this point represents his most life-threatening injury. Once the shock and ongoing bleeding are managed, the other issues can be dealt with.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EATLS (Advanced Trauma and Life Support) guidelines recommend the following specific indications for thoracotomy:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETraumatic circulatory arrest after previously-witnessed signs of life\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnresponsive hypotension despite aggressive fluid resuscitation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERapid exsanguination via chest tube (relevant in this case):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026gt;1500mL at insertion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026gt;200mL/hr for the first 2-4hrs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chest trauma may be associated with large volume blood loss that may not be evident until a chest drain is inserted."],"references":["Bertoglio et al. Chest drain and thoracotomy for chest trauma. J Thorac Dis. 2019 Feb;11(Suppl 2):S186-S191. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30906584/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"130"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T22:06:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T22:06:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"130"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54769"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap